BGP Communities Attribute
1996", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC1997.html", target="_top", tooltip="This document describes an extension to BGP which may be used to pass additional information to both neighboring and remote BGP peers. [STANDARDS-TRACK]"];
  cites -> RFC1997;
  RFC4360 [label="RFC4360
BGP Extended Communities Attribute
2006", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC4360.html", target="_top", tooltip="This document describes the extended community BGP-4 attribute.  This attribute provides a mechanism for labeling information carried in BGP-4.  These labels can be used to control the distribution of this information, or for other applications. [STANDARDS-TRACK]"];
  cites -> RFC4360;
  RFC6793 [label="RFC6793
BGP Support for Four-Octet Autonomous
System (AS) Number Space
2012", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC6793.html", target="_top", tooltip="The Autonomous System number is encoded as a two-octet entity in the base BGP specification.  This document describes extensions to BGP to carry the Autonomous System numbers as four-octet entities.  This document obsoletes RFC 4893 and updates RFC 4271. [STANDARDS-TRACK]"];
  cites -> RFC6793;
  RFC2622 [label="RFC2622
Routing Policy Specification Language
(RPSL)
1999", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC2622.html", target="_top", tooltip="RPSL allows a network operator to be able to specify routing policies at various levels in the Internet hierarchy; for example at the Autonomous System (AS) level.  At the same time, policies can be specified with sufficient detail in RPSL so that low level router configurations can be generated from them.  RPSL is extensible; new routing protocols and new protocol features can be introduced at any time. [STANDARDS-TRACK]"];
  cites -> RFC2622;
